WEBVTT

00:00:00.010 --> 00:00:00.820
How are folks doing?

00:00:00.880 --> 00:00:05.940
This is going to be, this is going to start,

00:00:05.940 --> 00:00:07.340
I just want to preface something.

00:00:07.350 --> 00:00:08.800
This is going to start as a little bit of a tur

00:00:08.810 --> 00:00:10.370
d in the punch bowl kind of presentation.

00:00:10.400 --> 00:00:13.130
I want to promise you it's not going to end there

00:00:13.150 --> 00:00:13.360
.

00:00:13.420 --> 00:00:16.960
This sub-conference is called At Science, and so

00:00:16.960 --> 00:00:20.510
I'm doing a little bit of At Social Science today because

00:00:20.510 --> 00:00:21.840
I'm a social scientist.

00:00:21.840 --> 00:00:24.820
I'm a PhD student in communications at the University of Pennsylvania

00:00:24.820 --> 00:00:25.010
.

00:00:26.870 --> 00:00:29.800
At protocol is really good for a couple of things for social

00:00:29.800 --> 00:00:30.660
scientists.

00:00:30.670 --> 00:00:33.080
First off, there's everything that Sophie just talked about,

00:00:33.080 --> 00:00:35.320
which is fantastic, and I forgot to actually mention here,

00:00:35.320 --> 00:00:37.900
but in terms of the experiments that enables you to run,

00:00:37.910 --> 00:00:41.810
if you have spoken to any social scientist who is studying media

00:00:41.810 --> 00:00:45.020
effects on social media, they will talk about that exact same

00:00:45.020 --> 00:00:48.010
complaint, which is we have absolutely no control over what is

00:00:48.010 --> 00:00:50.830
going on, and so we are just left to go through

00:00:50.990 --> 00:00:52.260
behavioral data.

00:00:52.270 --> 00:00:54.500
But even within that, it's gotten a lot harder recently

00:00:54.560 --> 00:00:58.210
because we're living in what some folks call the post-

00:00:58.210 --> 00:01:00.670
API age, where following a bunch of stuff in the

00:01:00.670 --> 00:01:03.900
last five to ten years, a bunch of APIs on most

00:01:03.930 --> 00:01:08.350
big social media platforms were either made private, or if you

00:01:08.350 --> 00:01:10.820
are allowed to access them, in the case of X,

00:01:10.820 --> 00:01:13.060
the rates are really exorbitant, or you have

00:01:13.060 --> 00:01:16.300
to get your, I think in the case of TikTok,

00:01:16.310 --> 00:01:19.660
you have to get every specific part of your project approved by

00:01:19.660 --> 00:01:22.180
TikTok, which does have a sort of chilling effect, right

00:01:22.180 --> 00:01:24.340
, if you want to ask these really kind of critical questions

00:01:24.340 --> 00:01:26.340
, and you have to go to TikTok and say, hey

00:01:26.370 --> 00:01:28.440
, I want to ask really critical questions about you, will

00:01:28.500 --> 00:01:29.290
you give me permission?

00:01:29.310 --> 00:01:31.760
It's kind of an awkward process, or you have to

00:01:31.760 --> 00:01:34.400
use something like Meta's content library, which is the

00:01:34.400 --> 00:01:37.740
official way you can look at like Facebook and Instagram information,

00:01:37.750 --> 00:01:40.560
and the problem with the platform like that is that it does

00:01:40.560 --> 00:01:43.290
, you have to do everything through a custom browser that they

00:01:43.470 --> 00:01:45.510
have, because they're really worried in the wake of Cambridge

00:01:45.510 --> 00:01:48.060
Analytica about how folks use their data, and that is

00:01:48.060 --> 00:01:51.350
a good concern to have, but the way their solution ends

00:01:51.350 --> 00:01:54.970
up working really limits the amount of data analysis you're able

00:01:55.040 --> 00:01:57.150
to do, so it's not great, and one of

00:01:57.150 --> 00:02:00.480
the really nice benefits of ad protocol, permission spaces notwith

00:02:00.480 --> 00:02:03.370
standing, is that because everything is public, you kind of

00:02:03.370 --> 00:02:06.110
avoid all of those concerns about pricey, hard-to

00:02:06.110 --> 00:02:07.560
-use, or hard-to-access data.

00:02:08.310 --> 00:02:10.030
But the second thing, and this is what I think is

00:02:10.030 --> 00:02:13.330
more interesting, is that it qualitatively changes the type of

00:02:13.390 --> 00:02:15.140
question you're able to ask.

00:02:15.150 --> 00:02:18.300
So I'm coming from the political economy of communications, where

00:02:18.300 --> 00:02:22.000
we ask questions about how does the ownership of different media systems

00:02:22.060 --> 00:02:24.550
affect the type of media that is produced.

00:02:24.570 --> 00:02:27.360
They've asked a lot of really interesting questions in the past

00:02:27.360 --> 00:02:27.580
.

00:02:27.590 --> 00:02:30.160
There's a lot of stuff, there's a whole literature

00:02:30.310 --> 00:02:32.740
that I won't go into here, looking into like how

00:02:32.740 --> 00:02:37.320
does commercial media funding affect the nature of journalism, what sort

00:02:37.320 --> 00:02:40.220
of effects does it have on a democratic society, all these

00:02:40.220 --> 00:02:43.740
really important questions, and folks have done really good thinking about

00:02:43.740 --> 00:02:46.470
what that means for social media, but there's kind of

00:02:46.480 --> 00:02:48.970
never been an A-B comparison you can make, right

00:02:48.970 --> 00:02:49.140
?

00:02:49.150 --> 00:02:52.390
If you look at journalism, you can say, look,

00:02:52.390 --> 00:02:55.280
there are some newspapers that are funded by advertisers, there are

00:02:55.280 --> 00:02:59.170
some that are more publicly funded, but on social media,

00:02:59.170 --> 00:03:02.180
in the last 20 years, it's mostly been the same

00:03:02.180 --> 00:03:05.310
handful of dominant players, all of whom are operating as privately

00:03:05.310 --> 00:03:08.180
owned corporations, where they have the same incentive set, and

00:03:08.180 --> 00:03:10.520
there's very little you can do.

00:03:10.580 --> 00:03:14.380
With Blue Sky existing, though, you can start to ask

00:03:14.380 --> 00:03:16.720
these questions about like what would a different model look like,

00:03:16.730 --> 00:03:19.790
and so a great example of this is some work looking at

00:03:19.800 --> 00:03:24.720
the different third-party services offered on Blue Sky, and

00:03:24.720 --> 00:03:28.220
it's kind of a digital ethnography and a little bit

00:03:28.230 --> 00:03:31.770
of a qualitative project, but their main finding is that if

00:03:31.790 --> 00:03:34.650
you look at feeds, starter packs, moderation lists, and

00:03:34.650 --> 00:03:38.030
labels, there is not a lot of financial modernization.

00:03:38.120 --> 00:03:40.490
I don't think this will be a huge surprise to most

00:03:40.490 --> 00:03:43.030
of the folks in this room, but most of these things

00:03:43.050 --> 00:03:44.690
are built because, hey, I'm part of a community

00:03:44.690 --> 00:03:46.470
, I care about this community, I want to go build

00:03:46.470 --> 00:03:47.340
this tool for them.

00:03:47.400 --> 00:03:49.840
I think many of the presentations that we've heard today,

00:03:49.850 --> 00:03:52.040
that's how they start is I wanted this thing to exist

00:03:52.040 --> 00:03:53.780
and I went and built it, and that is great and

00:03:53.780 --> 00:03:56.030
that is not necessarily a bad thing, but it does change

00:03:56.030 --> 00:03:58.560
kind of qualitatively the type of network that we're working

00:03:58.560 --> 00:03:59.000
within.

00:03:59.060 --> 00:04:02.030
There's also this point about supply often outstripping

00:04:02.170 --> 00:04:02.580
demand.

00:04:02.580 --> 00:04:04.800
A lot of folks will go and build a specific tool for

00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:05.380
themselves.

00:04:05.380 --> 00:04:09.180
I know many folks here have went and built a feed because

00:04:09.190 --> 00:04:10.620
they wanted to see one thing specific.

00:04:11.830 --> 00:04:13.560
The side effect of that, though, is that most,

00:04:13.560 --> 00:04:15.760
if you look at where users are actually spending their time,

00:04:15.760 --> 00:04:18.720
a lot of them are just using whatever defaults are promoted

00:04:18.720 --> 00:04:21.280
to them through Blue Sky or using a handful of larger actors

00:04:21.290 --> 00:04:21.510
.

00:04:21.580 --> 00:04:24.700
Which brings me to my question, which is how decentralized is

00:04:24.700 --> 00:04:25.540
Blue Sky, really?

00:04:25.550 --> 00:04:27.660
Like, we're a decentralized network, right?

00:04:27.670 --> 00:04:28.580
That's what we're here for.

00:04:28.580 --> 00:04:29.380
We're decentralized.

00:04:29.390 --> 00:04:30.180
That's what we talk about.

00:04:30.190 --> 00:04:33.840
Now, I want to say I'm building this work.

00:04:33.850 --> 00:04:35.910
Balduf et al., who wrote one of the first

00:04:35.920 --> 00:04:38.490
academic papers I could find on Blue Sky, did a similar

00:04:38.490 --> 00:04:43.530
measurement of handles in 2024 and then a guy named Kuba

00:04:43.530 --> 00:04:46.480
Suter, who I have not met, I do not

00:04:46.480 --> 00:04:49.280
know, but I learned that he did a lot of this

00:04:49.280 --> 00:04:51.570
data analysis similarly, literally yesterday.

00:04:51.590 --> 00:04:53.340
So a shout out to him.

00:04:53.350 --> 00:04:55.400
He has a live feed of a similar version of this data

00:04:55.460 --> 00:04:57.900
because I'm always, this presentation is going to be a

00:04:57.900 --> 00:04:59.270
lot of me getting nerd sniped.

00:04:59.340 --> 00:05:03.580
Okay, there are a couple ways you can measure decentralization

00:05:03.630 --> 00:05:05.460
and this is where I leave a little asterisk there

00:05:05.470 --> 00:05:06.300
because this is out of date.

00:05:06.300 --> 00:05:08.560
I would like a more rigorous way to go through this and

00:05:08.580 --> 00:05:11.230
so since there are out proto developers here, I thought if

00:05:11.260 --> 00:05:13.340
anyone would know how to do this in a better way,

00:05:13.340 --> 00:05:13.980
it would be you guys.

00:05:14.030 --> 00:05:16.850
The first is you go to the relay, you say,

00:05:16.850 --> 00:05:18.420
hey, can you give me your list of hosts?

00:05:18.430 --> 00:05:20.020
We go to the hosts, we say, hey, can

00:05:20.020 --> 00:05:22.710
you give us a list of repos you're storing and

00:05:22.710 --> 00:05:23.900
you measure that.

00:05:23.910 --> 00:05:26.710
Now, the problem is not every personal data server is going

00:05:26.710 --> 00:05:28.690
to give you a list of repos.

00:05:28.700 --> 00:05:30.430
It's not always going to be accurate and it's not

00:05:30.460 --> 00:05:32.580
always going to tell you if that user is active and so

00:05:32.580 --> 00:05:34.320
the second way you do it is you go to PLC

00:05:34.320 --> 00:05:36.450
, you say, hey, can I scrape every action that

00:05:36.480 --> 00:05:38.700
has ever been taken and then from those actions, you say

00:05:38.700 --> 00:05:41.430
, hey, when is the last time each user updated where

00:05:41.430 --> 00:05:44.610
their data is stored and you combine that and the number you

00:05:44.610 --> 00:05:46.910
get is something like 99.

00:05:46.930 --> 00:05:49.500
7% of all accounts are owned by Blue Sky.

00:05:49.560 --> 00:05:53.070
That seems pretty centralized but okay, I know what you're

00:05:53.070 --> 00:05:53.420
saying.

00:05:53.420 --> 00:05:56.120
I know what every single one of you is saying but Billy

00:05:56.120 --> 00:05:57.460
, my name is Billy, by the way, hi.

00:05:57.470 --> 00:06:01.080
But Billy, it might be centralized but in practice, the

00:06:01.100 --> 00:06:03.600
people who are really spending time on the network, the folks

00:06:03.610 --> 00:06:05.570
who are posting every day, who are liking stuff, who

00:06:05.620 --> 00:06:07.790
are getting followed, those are us.

00:06:07.830 --> 00:06:10.370
We're the cool people and we go and we host our

00:06:10.370 --> 00:06:10.980
own data.

00:06:10.990 --> 00:06:12.780
So clearly, if you look in practice, it's not

00:06:12.800 --> 00:06:13.280
going to be the same.

00:06:13.290 --> 00:06:14.200
That's a great point.

00:06:14.210 --> 00:06:16.040
And so another way you can do it is you can look

00:06:16.110 --> 00:06:16.560
at the fire hose.

00:06:16.570 --> 00:06:18.440
You say, okay, let's look at the fire hose

00:06:18.440 --> 00:06:18.630
.

00:06:18.650 --> 00:06:21.020
Let's look at sample over the course of an hour or

00:06:21.080 --> 00:06:23.500
a day or a week and let's see how much activity

00:06:23.500 --> 00:06:26.290
is coming in and let's see for that activity who is

00:06:26.300 --> 00:06:29.950
being followed, who is being liked, and who is posting

00:06:29.960 --> 00:06:29.960
.

00:06:29.970 --> 00:06:32.050
And does that activity, is that more decentralized?

00:06:32.070 --> 00:06:34.730
So you do that, you resolve the ID, you look

00:06:34.730 --> 00:06:35.170
at the follows.

00:06:35.190 --> 00:06:36.220
It's not great.

00:06:36.300 --> 00:06:37.180
99.

00:06:37.200 --> 00:06:40.830
9% of follows are going to accounts hosted on Blue Sk

00:06:40.830 --> 00:06:41.300
ies PDS.

00:06:41.310 --> 00:06:42.270
Same with likes.

00:06:42.290 --> 00:06:45.790
The promising one is that if you look at posts, just

00:06:45.790 --> 00:06:49.110
over 1% of posts are made by folks who are self

00:06:49.120 --> 00:06:51.250
-hosting or using another place to host their data.

00:06:52.570 --> 00:06:54.470
This is the turd and the punch bowl part of the

00:06:54.480 --> 00:06:55.000
presentation.

00:06:55.060 --> 00:06:57.680
Now, I want to talk about a few other things,

00:06:57.740 --> 00:07:00.940
which is in talking about the atmosphere and talking about Blue Sky

00:07:00.940 --> 00:07:03.050
, we often talk about a credible exit or, as I

00:07:03.050 --> 00:07:05.940
like to think about it, like what would happen if 2022

00:07:05.940 --> 00:07:07.400
Twitter happened tomorrow?

00:07:07.410 --> 00:07:09.900
And there are a couple other concerns.

00:07:09.910 --> 00:07:11.260
This is the continuation of the turd.

00:07:11.270 --> 00:07:14.090
The first one is a lack of adoption and a challenge with

00:07:14.090 --> 00:07:14.500
funding.

00:07:15.440 --> 00:07:17.410
I think we are all aware of this.

00:07:17.430 --> 00:07:20.680
Paul Frazee, in his recent February, 2026

00:07:20.680 --> 00:07:22.570
, he wrote a little bit about this, how I think

00:07:22.570 --> 00:07:25.800
it is well understood that most of this stuff is still being

00:07:25.830 --> 00:07:28.520
owned and hosted by Blue Sky and that does present a certain

00:07:28.530 --> 00:07:29.220
level of problem.

00:07:29.230 --> 00:07:31.580
And that gets back to the paper I was referencing earlier,

00:07:31.640 --> 00:07:34.680
where oftentimes we are really, we are building these economies,

00:07:34.690 --> 00:07:37.780
but these economies are based off of subcultural capital.

00:07:37.790 --> 00:07:38.680
They're based on gifts.

00:07:39.130 --> 00:07:42.670
And although I think there are really promising moves in projects like

00:07:42.710 --> 00:07:45.560
Graze, the funding of these systems is not clear.

00:07:45.570 --> 00:07:48.750
It's also not clear for a user what benefit they get

00:07:48.790 --> 00:07:51.360
out of going out of their way to host their data somewhere

00:07:51.390 --> 00:07:51.740
else.

00:07:51.800 --> 00:07:53.960
That's not an easy solution.

00:07:53.970 --> 00:07:57.580
And I think it also reminds us that the folks in this

00:07:57.580 --> 00:08:00.210
room are going to be amongst the most technical users of Blue

00:08:00.240 --> 00:08:00.430
Sky.

00:08:00.450 --> 00:08:02.500
By way of example, a week ago I was visiting my

00:08:02.500 --> 00:08:03.000
grandparents.

00:08:03.060 --> 00:08:06.440
Boy, I tried explaining what I was presenting this weekend to

00:08:06.480 --> 00:08:06.780
them.

00:08:06.780 --> 00:08:08.660
I don't think a single part of it computed.

00:08:09.120 --> 00:08:11.140
I love them dearly, but if we want to have

00:08:11.140 --> 00:08:14.020
this as a protocol that serves everybody, we have to think

00:08:14.020 --> 00:08:17.080
about what incentives folks have to be actually decentralized.

00:08:17.140 --> 00:08:22.490
And this gets to the broader point of what the limits of

00:08:22.550 --> 00:08:23.500
what a protocol can do.

00:08:23.520 --> 00:08:26.990
A protocol is only as powerful as our willingness to follow what

00:08:26.990 --> 00:08:27.880
the protocol says.

00:08:27.890 --> 00:08:31.370
So if you think about it, if tomorrow Blue Sky Social

00:08:31.370 --> 00:08:33.460
, let's say it went worse of the worst, Elon

00:08:33.460 --> 00:08:35.950
Musk took it over tomorrow, and they said, we're

00:08:35.980 --> 00:08:37.020
actually not going to interface.

00:08:37.030 --> 00:08:39.520
You can tell us that you want to migrate your data tough

00:08:39.520 --> 00:08:41.280
nuggets, we're not going to let you do it.

00:08:41.340 --> 00:08:43.580
There's nothing really we could do.

00:08:43.590 --> 00:08:45.210
They could choose to hold on to your data.

00:08:45.230 --> 00:08:47.950
They could choose to make the platform no longer interoperable

00:08:47.990 --> 00:08:50.700
with anyone who's not hosted on Blue Sky Social directly.

00:08:50.710 --> 00:08:53.350
It wouldn't be easy for them, but if they choose

00:08:53.370 --> 00:08:56.200
to not follow the protocol, they don't have to.

00:08:56.210 --> 00:08:58.690
And this brings me, if anyone here is a lawyer,

00:08:58.730 --> 00:09:03.860
I know what the zero lawyers in this room are saying,

00:09:03.870 --> 00:09:06.740
but Billy, Blue Sky is a public benefit corporation.

00:09:06.740 --> 00:09:07.500
It's a great word.

00:09:07.510 --> 00:09:09.350
It means that you are legally in the U.

00:09:09.390 --> 00:09:09.600
S.

00:09:09.660 --> 00:09:12.700
allowed to have a responsibility that is not purely financial.

00:09:12.760 --> 00:09:15.080
First off, it is crazy that that needs to be specified

00:09:15.080 --> 00:09:15.200
.

00:09:15.230 --> 00:09:17.660
But second of all, it is a really nice thing.

00:09:17.670 --> 00:09:19.140
It's about a decade and a half old.

00:09:19.140 --> 00:09:24.170
I think 2013, Delaware is the state where most American corporations

00:09:24.170 --> 00:09:27.530
, most American businesses are incorporated, is in Delaware.

00:09:27.570 --> 00:09:29.300
They started allowing it.

00:09:29.310 --> 00:09:31.670
The challenge is, in 2019, there was a change in

00:09:31.670 --> 00:09:34.040
the law, stick with me, that changed it from,

00:09:34.050 --> 00:09:36.660
if you want to go from being a public benefit corporation,

00:09:36.740 --> 00:09:39.840
meaning you have some mission, to not one of those anymore

00:09:39.850 --> 00:09:45.680
, it only requires 50% of your shareholders to vote against

00:09:45.690 --> 00:09:46.160
that.

00:09:46.170 --> 00:09:49.580
The consequence of that is we are now in a place where

00:09:49.580 --> 00:09:52.630
if 50% of the folks who own Blue Sky decided to

00:09:52.630 --> 00:09:55.690
no longer have a decentralized mission, they could do that tomorrow

00:09:55.760 --> 00:09:57.780
, and there would be nothing you could do to stop them

00:09:57.780 --> 00:09:57.930
.

00:09:57.950 --> 00:09:59.620
Which brings me to another point, I'm going to say

00:09:59.670 --> 00:10:01.740
this really quietly because of the sponsors on the wall, we

00:10:01.760 --> 00:10:03.420
don't know who owns Blue Sky.

00:10:03.430 --> 00:10:04.550
That information is not public.

00:10:04.560 --> 00:10:06.250
We know the list of people, but we do not know

00:10:06.270 --> 00:10:08.540
how that is distributed amongst those different owners.

00:10:08.550 --> 00:10:12.100
So it's a concern because if they wanted to tomorrow,

00:10:12.110 --> 00:10:15.340
the entire protocol for everything valuable that's built, there is

00:10:15.340 --> 00:10:18.100
nothing keeping that Blue Sky information from being re-silo

00:10:18.100 --> 00:10:18.380
ed.

00:10:18.410 --> 00:10:21.220
Okay, we're going to take a breath.

00:10:21.230 --> 00:10:23.220
Let's talk about some good stuff.

00:10:23.300 --> 00:10:27.650
First off, the move towards independently spinning off the PLC

00:10:27.650 --> 00:10:29.270
directory is a really good one.

00:10:29.650 --> 00:10:32.150
That will at least allow so that your identity can be shared

00:10:32.150 --> 00:10:32.670
elsewhere.

00:10:32.680 --> 00:10:34.700
I think that is a really promising first step.

00:10:34.710 --> 00:10:36.910
The second thing is these data backups.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:41.160
I met Fig briefly earlier in the elevator today.

00:10:41.220 --> 00:10:42.520
Very nice person.

00:10:42.580 --> 00:10:45.120
Like Hubble, are really valuable, right?

00:10:45.180 --> 00:10:46.820
Because we want to be able to say, listen, not

00:10:46.840 --> 00:10:48.850
only can I move my identity over, but I can also

00:10:48.880 --> 00:10:50.000
move the data with that over.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.590
So having these public backups is a really useful way of doing

00:10:52.590 --> 00:10:55.200
that, especially for users who a priori might not think

00:10:55.210 --> 00:10:57.240
to go out and make a copy of their data.

00:10:57.860 --> 00:10:59.960
I also want to give a shout out to the folks in

00:10:59.960 --> 00:11:03.240
this room who are working on building other forms of PDS

00:11:03.240 --> 00:11:03.780
s.

00:11:03.820 --> 00:11:04.860
I'm thinking of Black Sky.

00:11:04.900 --> 00:11:05.870
I'm thinking of Euro Sky.

00:11:05.940 --> 00:11:06.850
North Sky.

00:11:06.870 --> 00:11:09.860
There are any number of these, but people really think,

00:11:09.870 --> 00:11:12.130
doing the hard work of thinking about how do we build these

00:11:12.160 --> 00:11:12.620
other communities.

00:11:12.630 --> 00:11:15.690
That is incredibly valuable and God willing, we can reach a

00:11:15.720 --> 00:11:18.820
decentralization through those efforts where this whole presentation is a mo

00:11:18.820 --> 00:11:19.340
ot point.

00:11:19.890 --> 00:11:21.370
And finally, all of you wonderful folks.

00:11:21.380 --> 00:11:23.360
I want to be clear when I'm saying all this.

00:11:23.360 --> 00:11:25.650
I'm just trying to be honest about the situation that we

00:11:25.650 --> 00:11:26.390
find ourselves in.

00:11:26.420 --> 00:11:28.840
I do not think this is a foregone conclusion, nor

00:11:28.840 --> 00:11:30.900
do I think these are unsolvable problems.

00:11:30.910 --> 00:11:33.190
And so I'm really, I've been really motivated over

00:11:33.220 --> 00:11:36.470
the last couple days speaking to everybody and seeing how much everyone

00:11:36.470 --> 00:11:36.860
cares.

00:11:36.920 --> 00:11:39.990
Of course, I said I got nerd sniped and nine

00:11:39.990 --> 00:11:42.690
days before this presentation, Lawrence Hoff wrote a blog post about

00:11:42.690 --> 00:11:43.340
exactly this.

00:11:43.350 --> 00:11:46.480
So thanks for sitting with me while I repeated stuff that he

00:11:46.500 --> 00:11:46.900
mentioned.

00:11:47.320 --> 00:11:49.210
I really like this quote of him and I'm going to

00:11:49.210 --> 00:11:51.700
abuse Scott, your metaphor about the party.

00:11:51.760 --> 00:11:53.990
Not only do we have a good party set up, I

00:11:53.990 --> 00:11:55.180
think we have a great party going.

00:11:55.190 --> 00:11:57.100
The problem is everyone's stuck in the kitchen.

00:11:57.120 --> 00:11:58.810
It's getting a little cramped in here and we really

00:11:58.810 --> 00:12:00.580
love it if some people moved to the living room, some

00:12:00.580 --> 00:12:01.860
people moved to the balconies.

00:12:01.860 --> 00:12:03.250
You've actually got a little bit more spaced out.

00:12:03.290 --> 00:12:04.520
That's my presentation.

00:12:04.580 --> 00:12:05.510
Thanks, guys.

00:12:05.530 --> 00:12:12.080
Thanks, Billy.

00:12:12.090 --> 00:12:13.120
Any questions?

00:12:17.330 --> 00:12:23.540
Hey, I'm Daniel.

00:12:23.540 --> 00:12:24.970
I do protocol stuff at Blue Sky.

00:12:24.990 --> 00:12:27.300
Don't worry, you're not offending any of us

00:12:27.300 --> 00:12:27.940
by saying this.

00:12:27.950 --> 00:12:29.120
We basically agree with you.

00:12:29.300 --> 00:12:32.560
And I'm talking about very similar stuff in my talk on

00:12:32.560 --> 00:12:33.030
Sunday.

00:12:33.050 --> 00:12:36.060
One of my questions is, like, there's sort of

00:12:36.070 --> 00:12:37.220
this logical impossibility.

00:12:37.230 --> 00:12:39.580
Like, we want the network to decentralize more.

00:12:39.590 --> 00:12:42.390
There's sort of this logical impossibility for Blue Sky decentral

00:12:42.390 --> 00:12:42.910
izing it.

00:12:43.150 --> 00:12:46.530
Like, you almost need other parties to step in and take

00:12:46.530 --> 00:12:48.670
power and authority and control in the network.

00:12:48.760 --> 00:12:52.450
So, what do you think can encourage people to do that

00:12:52.450 --> 00:12:52.840
more?

00:12:52.900 --> 00:12:55.280
First off, it's really nice to meet you.

00:12:55.280 --> 00:12:56.080
I've read your stuff.

00:12:56.080 --> 00:12:57.530
I've read a lot of people's stuff in this room

00:12:57.530 --> 00:12:57.660
.

00:12:57.690 --> 00:12:58.000
Absolutely.

00:12:58.030 --> 00:13:01.800
I really was hoping I would end this presentation with a slide

00:13:01.830 --> 00:13:03.320
of here's all the things we can do.

00:13:03.330 --> 00:13:06.680
I think part of, but what I've thought about it

00:13:06.700 --> 00:13:08.560
more, again, I'm coming from a social science background

00:13:08.560 --> 00:13:08.680
.

00:13:08.690 --> 00:13:11.480
One of the things I want to push us towards thinking about

00:13:11.490 --> 00:13:13.930
just as a community is all of the, you know,

00:13:13.960 --> 00:13:15.740
we're talking about so-so technical systems, all the

00:13:15.740 --> 00:13:17.860
social ways that these networks are built up.

00:13:17.870 --> 00:13:20.420
And so I think my point here is not that there's

00:13:20.440 --> 00:13:22.200
an easy solution and I really wish there was.

00:13:22.210 --> 00:13:24.520
I can kind of spitball ideas against the wall.

00:13:24.530 --> 00:13:27.740
My point is more so to say that I think there is

00:13:27.740 --> 00:13:29.410
, just to make the point that there's a limit to

00:13:29.470 --> 00:13:31.950
what we can do with the protocol is really valuable and there

00:13:31.950 --> 00:13:33.330
's a lot of stuff that can be done, but that

00:13:33.330 --> 00:13:34.940
is insufficient to do it on its own.

00:13:34.970 --> 00:13:36.920
Now, I could start daydreaming with you.

00:13:36.930 --> 00:13:41.120
There's really good proposals with folks I've worked with and

00:13:41.140 --> 00:13:41.960
folks I've seen.

00:13:42.460 --> 00:13:45.680
Looking at like local acre institutions, so could we have,

00:13:45.690 --> 00:13:49.340
you know, public funding towards like local hosting of this?

00:13:49.340 --> 00:13:51.630
I mean, this is an ideal world where the government landscape

00:13:51.630 --> 00:13:53.810
looks different than it currently is and the funding landscape is different

00:13:53.810 --> 00:13:53.910
.

00:13:54.100 --> 00:13:56.880
There are questions about kind of, it's that kind of

00:13:56.890 --> 00:14:00.580
civil society question of can we rethink models and funding of social

00:14:00.590 --> 00:14:04.050
media and that goes again in this long history of debates about

00:14:04.130 --> 00:14:06.210
like public funding of journalism, for example.

00:14:06.300 --> 00:14:10.220
Those are some of my more optimistic takes and I would love

00:14:10.260 --> 00:14:11.200
to talk more after this.

00:14:11.790 --> 00:14:13.520
But generally, I do think we run into this issue where

00:14:13.580 --> 00:14:15.020
there's just a limit to what we can do technically.

00:14:15.200 --> 00:14:21.200
Anyone else?

